hook.real_world_problem:
You're importing Flipkart seller product data. The CSV looks simple — but:

```csv
product_id,name,price,description
P001,Wireless Mouse,799,"Compact, lightweight design"
P002,"Dell 27" Monitor",18999,"4K display, HDMI"
P003,USB Hub,499,Multiple ports
```

Naive parsing with `line.split(",")` completely breaks:

```java
// WRONG:
String[] cols = line.split(",");
// "Compact, lightweight design" → ['Compact', ' lightweight design'] — SPLIT INSIDE QUOTES!
// "Dell 27" Monitor" → broken — escaped quote inside field
```

Real CSV has rules:
- Fields can be quoted with `"`
- Quoted fields can contain commas (not delimiters)
- Quotes inside quoted fields are doubled: `""`
- Fields can span multiple lines if quoted

```java
// CORRECT — handle quoted fields:
List<String> fields = parseCSVLine("\"Compact, lightweight\",799");
// ["Compact, lightweight", "799"] — comma inside quotes is NOT a delimiter
```

And for JSON:
```java
// With Jackson — one-line read:
Product p = mapper.readValue("{\"id\":1,\"name\":\"Mouse\"}", Product.class);
String json = mapper.writeValueAsString(p);
```

Today you learn to process REAL data files — not toy examples.

concept_explanation.csv_parsing:
**Correct CSV parsing — state machine approach:**

```java
public static List<String> parseCSVLine(String line) {
    List<String> fields = new ArrayList<>();
    StringBuilder current = new StringBuilder();
    boolean inQuotes = false;

    for (int i = 0; i < line.length(); i++) {
        char c = line.charAt(i);

        if (c == '"') {
            if (inQuotes && i + 1 < line.length() && line.charAt(i+1) == '"') {
                current.append('"');  // escaped quote "" → "
                i++;  // skip next quote
            } else {
                inQuotes = !inQuotes;  // toggle quote mode
            }
        } else if (c == ',' && !inQuotes) {
            fields.add(current.toString());
            current.setLength(0);
        } else {
            current.append(c);
        }
    }
    fields.add(current.toString());  // last field
    return fields;
}

// Usage:
List<String> cols = parseCSVLine("\"Dell 27\"\" Monitor\",18999,\"4K display, HDMI\"");
// ["Dell 27\" Monitor", "18999", "4K display, HDMI"]
```

This handles: commas in quotes, escaped double-quotes. For production code with multi-line fields, header parsing, and encoding — use Apache Commons CSV or OpenCSV.

concept_explanation.writing_csv:
**Writing correct CSV:**

```java
public static String toCSVField(String value) {
    if (value == null) return "";
    // Need to quote if: contains comma, double-quote, or newline
    boolean needsQuoting = value.contains(",") ||
                           value.contains("\"") ||
                           value.contains("\n");
    if (!needsQuoting) return value;
    // Escape double-quotes by doubling them:
    return "\"" + value.replace("\"", "\"\"") + "\"";
}

// Build a CSV line:
List<String> fields = Arrays.asList("Dell 27\" Monitor", "18999", "4K, HDMI");
String csvLine = fields.stream()
    .map(App::toCSVField)
    .collect(Collectors.joining(","));
// "Dell 27\"\" Monitor",18999,"4K, HDMI"

// Write CSV file:
try (PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter(new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("output.csv")))) {
    pw.println("name,price,description");  // header
    for (Product p : products) {
        pw.printf("%s,%s,%s%n",
            toCSVField(p.getName()),
            toCSVField(String.valueOf(p.getPrice())),
            toCSVField(p.getDescription()));
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.jackson_basics:
**Jackson — Java's most popular JSON library:**

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode;

// ObjectMapper is thread-safe — create ONCE, reuse everywhere:
ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();

// ===== READING JSON =====

// JSON string → POJO (Plain Old Java Object):
String json = "{\"name\":\"Aisha\",\"age\":28,\"city\":\"Hyderabad\"}";
Person person = mapper.readValue(json, Person.class);
System.out.println(person.getName());  // Aisha

// JSON file → POJO:
Person fromFile = mapper.readValue(new File("person.json"), Person.class);

// JSON → List:
List<Person> people = mapper.readValue(
    "[{\"name\":\"Aisha\"},{\"name\":\"Raj\"}]",
    mapper.getTypeFactory().constructCollectionType(List.class, Person.class)
);

// ===== WRITING JSON =====

// POJO → JSON string:
Person aisha = new Person("Aisha", 28, "Hyderabad");
String jsonOut = mapper.writeValueAsString(aisha);
// {"name":"Aisha","age":28,"city":"Hyderabad"}

// POJO → formatted JSON:
String pretty = mapper.writerWithDefaultPrettyPrinter().writeValueAsString(aisha);
// Indented, readable JSON

// POJO → file:
mapper.writeValue(new File("output.json"), aisha);
```

**POJO requirements:**
- Public no-arg constructor (or @JsonCreator)
- Getters for serialization (write)
- Setters OR @JsonProperty for deserialization (read)

concept_explanation.json_node:
**JsonNode — tree model for dynamic JSON:**

When you don't know the structure upfront, use JsonNode:

```java
String json = "{\"symbol\":\"TCS\",\"price\":3890,\"change\":+4.1}";
JsonNode root = mapper.readTree(json);

// Navigate the tree:
String symbol = root.get("symbol").asText();     // "TCS"
double price  = root.get("price").asDouble();    // 3890.0
booleans has  = root.has("volume");              // false

// JSON array:
JsonNode arr = mapper.readTree("[1,2,3]");
for (JsonNode element : arr) {
    System.out.println(element.asInt());
}

// Nested:
JsonNode user = mapper.readTree("{\"address\":{\"city\":\"Hyderabad\"}}");
String city = user.path("address").path("city").asText();  // 'Hyderabad'
// path() returns MissingNode (not null) if absent — safe to chain

// Build JSON programmatically:
ObjectNode obj = mapper.createObjectNode();
obj.put("name", "Aisha");
obj.put("age", 28);
ArrayNode arr2 = mapper.createArrayNode();
arr2.add("coding").add("chess");
obj.set("hobbies", arr2);
System.out.println(mapper.writeValueAsString(obj));
// {"name":"Aisha","age":28,"hobbies":["coding","chess"]}
```

concept_explanation.csv_to_json:
**Transforming CSV to JSON — the practical combo:**

```java
// Read CSV, produce JSON array:
ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
ArrayNode results = mapper.createArrayNode();

try (BufferedReader br = Files.newBufferedReader(Path.of("products.csv"))) {
    String[] headers = parseCSVLine(br.readLine()).toArray(new String[0]);

    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
        List<String> values = parseCSVLine(line);
        ObjectNode node = mapper.createObjectNode();
        for (int i = 0; i < headers.length && i < values.size(); i++) {
            node.put(headers[i], values.get(i));
        }
        results.add(node);
    }
}

// Write pretty JSON:
String jsonOutput = mapper.writerWithDefaultPrettyPrinter()
    .writeValueAsString(results);
Files.writeString(Path.of("products.json"), jsonOutput);
System.out.println("Converted " + results.size() + " products to JSON");
```

